Here are the step-by-step solutions to complete both exercises for the InfyTel application.
Exercise 1: Service Account & Manual Token Association
Since Kubernetes 1.24+, token secrets are no longer automatically generated for ServiceAccounts. To fulfill the requirement of associating a manual token via a secret, we use the kubernetes.io/service-account.nameannotation.
Step 1: Create the Service Account
Create the service account named InfyTel_SA:
Bash

kubectl create serviceaccount infytel-sa
(Note: Kubernetes resource names are typically lowercase; we will use infytel-sa and infytel-secret for resource definitions to comply with DNS-1123 standards).
Step 2: Create the Secret and Manually Generate the Token
Create a file named infytel-secret.yaml with the special token type and link it to your service account:
YAML

apiVersion: v1
kind: Secret
metadata:
  name: infytel-secret
  annotations:
    kubernetes.io/service-account.name: "infytel-sa"
type: kubernetes.io/service-account-token
Apply the secret:
Bash

kubectl apply -f infytel-secret.yaml
Kubernetes will detect this annotation and automatically populate a long-lived API token into the secret. You can verify the token generation by running:
Bash

kubectl describe secret infytel-secret
Step 3: Apply the Service Account to the Pods
In your InfyTel application deployment or pod definition, add the serviceAccountName field under the specblock:
YAML

apiVersion: v1
kind: Pod
metadata:
  name: infytel-customer-service
spec:
  serviceAccountName: infytel-sa  # Associates the pod with your SA
  containers:
    - name: infytel-app-container
      image: nginx:alpine
Step 4: Verification
Verify that the pod is actively utilizing the new service account identity:
Bash

kubectl get pod infytel-customer-service -o jsonpath='{.spec.serviceAccountName}'
Expected Output: infytel-sa
Exercise 2: Fine-grained Access Control (RBAC)
Kubernetes does not have a native User API object. User authentication (like joey) is usually managed via external certificates or identity providers. However, authorization is handled in-cluster via Role-Based Access Control (RBAC).
Step 1: Create the Reader Role
Create a file named infytel-reader-role.yaml to configure the specified constrained permissions:
YAML

apiVersion: rbac.authorization.k8s.io/v1
kind: Role
metadata:
  name: InfyTel_reader
rules:
- apiGroups: [""] # "" indicates the core API group
  resources: ["pods"]
  verbs: ["get", "list"]
Apply the role:
Bash

kubectl apply -f infytel-reader-role.yaml
Step 2: Bind the Role to User "joey"
Create a file named infytel-rolebinding.yaml to map the newly created permissions specifically to Joey:
YAML

apiVersion: rbac.authorization.k8s.io/v1
kind: RoleBinding
metadata:
  name: infytel-reader-binding
subjects:
- kind: User
  name: joey
  apiGroup: rbac.authorization.k8s.io
roleRef:
  kind: Role
  name: InfyTel_reader
  apiGroup: rbac.authorization.k8s.io
Apply the binding:
Bash

kubectl apply -f infytel-rolebinding.yaml
Step 3: Test Joey's Authorization
You do not need to log in as Joey to test this. You can leverage the kubectl auth can-i impersonation command to test access on his behalf:
	1	Test if joey can list pods (Should be YES): Bash  kubectl auth can-i list pods --as=joey Output: yes
	3	Test if joey can delete pods (Should be NO): Bash  kubectl auth can-i delete pods --as=joey  Output: no
	5	Test if joey can look at other resources like services (Should be NO): Bash  kubectl auth can-i list services --as=joey  Output: no

============================


[14:33:48] system@controlplane:~/kube/serviceaccount/roles-rolebindings$ kubectl create role InfyTel_reader --resource="pod,deployment" --verb="get"
role.rbac.authorization.k8s.io/InfyTel_reader created
[14:34:35] system@controlplane:~/kube/serviceaccount/roles-rolebindings$ kubectl create rolebinding infytel-reader-binding --role=InfyTel_reader \
> --user=joey
rolebinding.rbac.authorization.k8s.io/infytel-reader-binding created
[14:35:41] system@controlplane:~/kube/serviceaccount/roles-rolebindings$ kubectl auth can-i list pods --as=joey
no
[14:35:59] system@controlplane:~/kube/serviceaccount/roles-rolebindings$ kubectl auth can-i get pods --as=joey
yes
